{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel0 \b \fs36 NAME\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b hsguard} - Program to detect changes in the file system\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel0 \b \fs36 SYNOPSIS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 hsguard creates a database from the configurable directories. Each file is checked individually and a CRC checksum (OLDSTYLE) is generated. Once the hard drive is included in the database every file can be checked for (unwanted) changes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This is precisely the purpose of hsguard. Hard drives (HDDs) age and if data is not read the drive may \u8220"forget\u8221" a bit.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I have HDDs running around the clock as backup systems, local file sharing, etc. I want to keep the data on these drives for many years.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Additionally, this makes it possible to detect if malware is in the process of encrypting all your data.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This is where \u8220"hsguard\u8221" comes in. hsguard stores all important information about a file. A file that has been changed is normally updated in the database. A CRC32 is calculated for each file. The checksum is saved per file and can be checked against.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Position, name, file size, file modification date, and the CRC32 are stored. Check counters and the date of inclusion can also be retrieved from the database.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In a cron job, hsguard [\u8211-update] \u8211-check can be called, where different files can then be checked. These are selected at random. An update adds new or changed files beforehand.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 With many options, the data can be listed and verified. Thus, in case of an incident, the database will be a helpful supplement.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 IMPORTANT! hsguard will not modify the contents of any hard drive. It will not delete or add any files. The only exception is the database itself. \u8220"hsguard \u8211-create\u8221" will, once, create a hsguard.rc. This file will not be overwritten. However, all parameters can also be specified on the command line.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 hsguard only requires read access to the data.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 hsguard can be configured in many ways: config file, exclude file, and command-line switches.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If hsguard is started for the first time, it will complain that the file /etc/hsguard.rc is missing. With \u8220"hsguard \u8211-create\u8221", an initial version can be created, along with a subdirectory /var/hsguard. An example can be found in the file hsguard_sample.rc.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel0 \b \fs36 DESCRIPTION\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 hsguard reads the file system and stores basic data. If a file is not present or has changed (fsize/mtime), a CRC32 checksum is generated for the file. This checksum is checked and an alert is triggered if necessary.\par}
