{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 DATABASE=\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The database itself. This can usefully be located under /var. Together with \u8211-initDB, this can be created as a basic configuration. For this, it must have read/write permissions. {\i --db overrides the file specified in the RC file}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 BASE=\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 BASE for everything specified. Where should the database be created from? This line should definitely be adjusted. For example, the path to the data to be protected could be /server/pictures or similar. {\i -b  overrides this}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 VERBOSE=\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Represents the log level. The higher the level, the more information about the tasks performed can be found in the log file or on the screen. More finely tuned via the special switch {\i \u8211-noscreen} .\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Verbosity levels are supported from 0-4 or better:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\f1 ROOT  0 :} Only system errors\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\f1 FAIL  1 :} Only messages that include errors\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\f1 USER  2 :} Default setting. Information about the start and end of each action is output\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\f1 INFO  3 :} This can be a lot of messages\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\f1 DEVL  4 :} Better not to look at this\u8212-intended only for developers\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 EXCLUDE=\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are folders that do not need to be searched, e.g., temp folders or the folder of this database. The files/directories are listed line by line, and with \u8216'?\u8217' and \u8217'*\u8217' you can exclude multiple items. A \u8216'#\u8217' at the beginning of a line is a comment. More on this topic {\b under: {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "#EXCLUDEFILE"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Exclude-File
}}}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 NOSCREEN=\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Can be Y/N. If Y, almost all output is only written to the log file and no longer displayed on the screen. Messages are only available in the log file. -s- on the command line can disable this behavior, even if NOSCREEN=Y is specified. It is recommended to comment out this line when setting up.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 EMERGENCY=\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Here you specify how \u8211-testDB should handle errors, including their repetition. The PANIC option is expressly recommended.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\f1 PANIC     :} Immediate abort. Program ends with error level 99\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\f1 COUNT=    :} The specified number of errors is counted. STOP at 0\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\f1 SKIP      :} Checked, but no further action is taken\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\f1 ABORT     :} Ends \u8220"normally\u8221" with error level 1. COUNT!\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\f1 UPDATE    :} Even in case of errors, the lastchk date is updated\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\f1 UPDATEALL :} As above, but also updates new size, CRC, FMTime\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i -e or \u8211-emergency can override these settings}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 ANSICOLOR=\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Many outputs are color-coded for better distinction. Y/N can disable the output of ANSI colors. If Y, colors can also be varied further. These can be viewed in the sample file.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 EXADD=\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Here you can ignore a file or even a directory. It\u8217's much better to use {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "#RC-EXCLUDE"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
RCexclude
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 WARNWBS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This parameter triggers a \u8220"warning\u8221" when a \u8220"large file\u8221" is detected. This can be useful if the files to be checked are not connected via the fastest connection. To prevent the cursor from appearing frozen while waiting, a file size can be set here. The warning is issued at user level. Specify in human-readable format like 1TB or 10MB. Set to 0 to disable this behavior.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Default value is 16GB.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 FORWARD\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This can be used once to refer to another config. This is useful if you can refer to other configs (e.g., on the network). As a feature, the section can be specified directly. This might look like:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 FORWARD=/srv/pub/backup.rc,std\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Exclude Files\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are many good reasons to exclude certain files or entire directory trees. This can be done very simply with a single file in the exclude file. A comment begins with a \u8216'#\u8217'. Everything following is a comment.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Multiple files can each be added individually or captured using the built-in file globbing. This works for files that \u8216'ls\u8217' would find, like \u8217'ls /var/log/*.log\u8217'.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Additionally, there are some keywords that exclude something if a certain situation applies. For example:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 ifhost WKST-Conny /etc/pconly.rc\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 With each new line, the situation is re-evaluated. That is, no multi-line blocks. However, the \u8216'situation evaluations\u8217' can be nested arbitrarily deep. The following can be used in this way:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 ifhost WKST-Conny ifuser werner message "Don't break anything on Conny's PC"\par}
